The paper discusses the $CONGEST$ model for distributed network computing, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The focus of the paper is on the impact of limiting the throughput of a network on its capacity to solve tasks efficiently, which is related to the field of Network Information Theory (cs.NI). The paper also presents algorithms for solving problems such as Minimum Spanning Tree and Single Source Shortest Path, which are topics in the field of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Algorithmic Game Theory (cs.AL). Finally, the paper discusses the concept of bandwidth insensitivity, which is related to Information Theory (cs.IT).
